Introduction

This project selected the “US Accident Injury Dataset” dataset from Data.gov, which is published by the US Department of Labour and spans 15 years (from 2000 to 2015). This dataset contains information on all accidents, injuries, and illnesses reported by mine operators and contractors. For project2, I use the data and domain I have explored in Project 1.

Part1 Classification

Overview

In this part, our goal is to define an accident by predicting its severity based on a number of variables. We define DAYS_AFFECT = (0.5 * DAYS_RESTRICT + DAYS_LOST) * NO_INJURIES and divide it into two categories [0, 8) and [8, inf), which respectively denote unaffected accident and affected accident.

Data preparation

Data Cleaning

In order to measure the severity of an accident, it is necessary for us to use the column DAYS_RESTRICT, DAYS_LOST and NO_INJURIES, which mean the number of days of restricted work activity, the number of actual days lost from work and the number of reportable injuries or illnesses resulting from the accident.

Considering that only less than 5% of the rows have NA values in these 3 columns that strongly correlated with DEGREE_INJURY (as we found in project1), we can group the data by DEGREE_INJURY and replace NA values with mean values in each group.

us_data <- read.csv("us_data_full.csv")

Define the target variable

Firstly, we indicate a new column DAYS_AFFECT by (0.5 * DAYS_RESTRICT + DAYS_LOST) * NO_INJURIES. Multiplied by the coefficient 0.5 because DAYS_RESTRICT means that it can still partially work, it is not as severe as DAYS_LOST. Next, We can divide it into two categories [0, 8) and [8, inf) with a cut-off of 8, which can keep a good class balance. Finally, because some data from DAYS_RESTRICT and DAYS_LOST is NA, we should filter some data.

data_classification <-  data_classification %>% mutate(DAYS_AFFECT = (DAYS_RESTRICT * 0.5 + DAYS_LOST) * NO_INJURIES ) %>%  mutate(DAYS_AFFECT_CLASS = cut(DAYS_AFFECT, breaks = c(0, 8, Inf), include.lowest=T, right=F)) %>% filter(!is.na(DAYS_AFFECT_CLASS))

split.train.cal.test <- function(x, split.column='CAL_YR', train.split.value=2010, cal.split.value=2013){
 rvalue <- x[,split.column]
 list( x[rvalue <= train.split.value, ],
 x[rvalue > train.split.value & rvalue <= cal.split.value, ],
 x[rvalue > cal.split.value, ])
}

Single variable model

Evaluation

The functions are used for model building and AUC.

mkPredC <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol, pos=pos.label) {
  pPos <- sum(outCol==pos)/length(outCol)
  naTab <- table(as.factor(outCol[is.na(varCol)]))
  pPosWna <- (naTab/sum(naTab))[pos]
  vTab <- table(as.factor(outCol),varCol)
  pPosWv <- (vTab[pos,]+1.0e-3*pPos)/(colSums(vTab)+1.0e-3)
  pred <- pPosWv[appCol]
  pred[is.na(appCol)] <- pPosWna
  pred[is.na(pred)] <- pPos
  pred
}
mkPredN <- function(outCol,varCol,appCol) {
  cuts <- unique(as.numeric(quantile(varCol, probs=seq(0, 1, 0.1), na.rm=T)))
  varC <- cut(varCol, cuts)
  appC <- cut(appCol, cuts)
  mkPredC(outCol, varC, appC)
}
calcAUC <- function(predcol, outcol, pos=pos.label) {
  perf <- performance(prediction(predcol, outcol==pos),'auc')
  as.numeric(perf@y.values)
}

Feature selection with log likelihood

We can use log likelihood to calculate the score of the single variable in calibration set. In order to select the appropriate variable as much as possible, it is critical that it can have a positive effect on the prediction. Therefore, we set the threshold as -1500, and variables with scores > -1500 will be used as feature variables for the prediction of models.

logLikelyhood <- function(outCol, predCol, pos=pos.label) {
  sum(ifelse(outCol==pos, log(predCol), log(1-predCol)))
}

baseRateCheck <- logLikelyhood(dCal[,outcome],  sum(dCal[,outcome]==pos.label)/length(dCal[,outcome]) )

selPredVars <- c()
selVars <- c()
minStep <- -1500

for(v in catvars) {
  pii <- paste('pred',v,sep='')
  liCheck <- 2*((sum(ifelse(dCal[,outcome]==pos.label, log(dCal[,pii]),log(1-dCal[,pii]))) - baseRateCheck))
  if(liCheck > minStep) {
    print(sprintf("%s, calibrationScore: %g",pii,liCheck))
    selPredVars <- c(selPredVars,pii)
    selVars <- c(selVars, v)
  }
}

}

Multivariate models

Evaluation

The following functions are created for the different models we will create. This function will return ROC plot, prediction distribution plot, precision / recall plot, confusion matrix and log likelihood.

evaluate_performance <- function(predictions, true.values, do.print=TRUE, threshold.value=0.5, pos=pos.label){
  eval.auc <- calcAUC(predictions, true.values)
  
  if(do.print){
    # ROC plot
    predObj <- prediction(predictions, true.values)
    perf <- performance(predObj, "tpr", "fpr")
    roc.df <- data.frame('fpr'=unlist(perf@x.values),'tpr'=unlist(perf@y.values),'threshold'=unlist(perf@alpha.values))
    p <- ggplot(roc.df, aes(x=fpr, y=tpr))+
      geom_line() +
      geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, linetype='dashed') +
      project_theme
    print(p)
    
    # Prediction distribution plot
    p <- ggplot(data.frame(predictions=predictions,  true.values=true.values),
          aes(x=predictions, color=true.values, linetype=true.values)) +
          geom_density()  + 
          labs(y = "Density", x = "Predicted probability") +
          project_theme
    print(p)
    
    # Precision/recall plot
    precObj <- performance(predObj, measure="prec")
    recObj <- performance(predObj, measure="rec")
    precision <- (precObj@y.values)[[1]]
    prec.x <- (precObj@x.values)[[1]]
    recall <- (recObj@y.values)[[1]]
    rocFrame <- data.frame(threshold=prec.x,precision=precision,recall=recall)
    pnull <-mean(true.values==pos)
    
    p1 <- ggplot(rocFrame, aes(x=threshold)) +
    geom_line(aes(y=precision)) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,1), ylim=c(0,1) )  + 
      project_theme
    p2 <- ggplot(rocFrame, aes(x=threshold)) +
    geom_line(aes(y=recall)) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0,1) ) + 
      project_theme
    grid.arrange(p1, p2, nrow = 2)
  
    # Confusion matrix table
    cat('Confusion Matrix')
    ctab.test <- table(pred=predictions > threshold.value, true.values=true.values)
    print(ctab.test)
    
    # Log likelihood
    pNull <- mean(true.values==pos.label)
    model.ll <- sum(ifelse(true.values==pos.label, log(predictions), log(1-predictions)))
    null.model.ll <- sum(ifelse(true.values==pos.label, log(pNull), log(1-pNull)))
    print(paste('Model Log Likelihood:', model.ll))
    print(paste('Null Model Log Likelihood:', null.model.ll))
    
  }
  
  eval.auc
}

evaluate_and_log_model <- function(model.type, model.name, predictions.train, true.values.train, predictions.cal, true.values.cal){
  train.auc <- evaluate_performance(predictions.train, true.values.train, do.print = FALSE)
  cal.auc <- evaluate_performance(predictions.cal, true.values.cal, do.print = TRUE)
  result <- data.frame(model.type = model.type,model.name = model.name,train.auc = train.auc,cal.auc = cal.auc)
  rownames(result) <- model.name
  models.auc <<- unique(rbind(models.auc, result))
  result
}

XGBOOST

XGBoost allows the use of linear classifiers in addition to regression trees and, in terms of the objective function, XGBoost’s objective function incorporates a canonical term that contains the number of leaf nodes and the L2 parametrization of the leaf scores to avoid overfitting and improve the generalisation of the model by controlling the complexity of the tree model.

It is a prediction tree based on classification and training, starting from the root node and progressively subdivided according to its test attributes towards its children in turn, allowing prediction and classification of the future based on known information. Logistic regression can be represented as: finding the best-fit parameters for the non-linear function SIGMOID, done by an optimisation algorithm, and can be seen as a perceptron problem. xGBoost in addition to regression trees, linear classifiers can also be used, and in terms of the objective function, XGBoost’s objective function incorporates a regular term to avoid overfitting and improve the generalisation of the model by controlling the complexity of the tree model, which make XGBoost show significant advantages in computational efficiency and prediction results.

Part2 Clustering

Overview

We found in Project 1 that the occurrence of accidents is closely related to time, we grouped the US Accident Injury Dataset according to the time of the accident. So we grouped the US Accident Injury Dataset according to the time of the accident and then hoped to group the new sample group by applying a clustering algorithm to these variables to design new indicators.

Data preparation

Generate a new table

To start with we group the time of the accident by year and quarter (CAL_YR,CAL_QTR), then we use a new table to keep some data about every group. The new table includes: – CAL_YR and CAL_QTR; – ACCIDENT_NUM: the number of accidents in specific quarter; – M_SHIFT_BEGIN_TIME: the average start shift time of accidents in specific quarter; dt.all.var.pred <- prediction(predict(decision.tree.all.vars, newdata=dCal)[,pos.label], dCal[,outcome]) – M_NO_INJURIES: the average number of injured per accident in specific quarter; – M_TOT_EXPER: the mean of total mining experience of affected personnel in specific quarter; – M_MINE_EXPER: the mean of total experience of affected personnel in specific quarter; – M_JOB_EXPER: the mean of experience in the job title of affected personnel in specific quarter

Before generating a new table, we need to clean the data, such as filtering out time greater than 2400 (because there are never more than 24 hours in a day) and replacing NA value with the mean (because the number of NA values represent only about 10%).

Also, We note that the last quarter (Q2 2015) accounted for only 2 rows out of the 2000 rows, which were removed in order to present outliers in subsequent studies.

Consturct the model

Finding the number of clusters k

Plot the CH index vs k

We can choose the CH metric to find the k-value, which measures the tightness within a class by calculating the sum of the squares of the distances between the points in the class and the class centre, and the separation of the data set by calculating the sum of the squares of the distances between the centroids of each class and the centroids of the data set, with the CH metric being obtained from the ratio of separation to tightness. Thereby, a larger CH represents a tighter class itself and a more dispersed class to class, i.e. a better clustering result.

# Calculate Euclidean distance
sqr_euDist <- function(x, y) {
  sum((x - y)^2) 
}

# Calculate the WSS of the cluster
wss <- function(clustermat) {
  c0 <- colMeans(clustermat)
  sum(apply( clustermat, 1, FUN=function(row) {sqr_euDist(row, c0)} ))
}
wss_total <- function(scaled_df, labels) {
  wss.sum <- 0 
  k <- length(unique(labels))
  for (i in 1:k)
    wss.sum <- wss.sum + wss(subset(scaled_df, labels == i))
  wss.sum
}

# Calculate the total sum of squares (rss) distance of data points about the global mean
tss <- function(scaled_df) {
  wss(scaled_df)
}

# Calculate the CH index using hierarchical clustering or k-mean clustering
CH_index <- function(scaled_df, kmax, method="kmeans") {
  if (!(method %in% c("kmeans", "hclust")))
    stop("method must be one of c('kmeans', 'hclust')")
  npts <- nrow(scaled_df)
  wss.value <- numeric(kmax) # create a vector of numeric type

  wss.value[1] <- wss(scaled_df)
  if (method == "kmeans") {
    # kmeans
    for (k in 2:kmax) {
      clustering <- kmeans(scaled_df, k, nstart=10, iter.max=100)
    wss.value[k] <- clustering$tot.withinss
    } 
  } else {
    # hclust
    d <- dist(scaled_df, method="euclidean")
    pfit <- hclust(d, method="ward.D2")
    for (k in 2:kmax) {
      labels <- cutree(pfit, k=k)
      wss.value[k] <- wss_total(scaled_df, labels)
    } 
  }
  bss.value <- tss(scaled_df) - wss.value # this is a vector
  B <- bss.value / (0:(kmax-1)) # also a vector
  W <- wss.value / (npts - 1:kmax) # also a vector
  data.frame(k = 1:kmax, CH_index = B/W, WSS = wss.value)
}

# Using a line graph to clearly show the CH values
crit.df <- CH_index(scaled_df, 10, method="hclust")

fig1 <- ggplot(crit.df, aes(x=k, y=CH_index)) +
  geom_point() + geom_line(colour="red") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10) +
  labs(y="CH index") + theme(text=element_text(size=20))

fig2 <- ggplot(crit.df, aes(x=k, y=WSS), color="blue") +
  geom_point() + geom_line(colour="blue") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=1:10, labels=1:10) +
  theme(text=element_text(size=20))

grid.arrange(fig1, fig2, nrow=1)

We can see that the CH value is maximised at k = 2, with another local maximum at k = 6.

Finally, we can draw a conclusion that the optimum number of clusters K should be 2. There are three reasons: – 1. From the plot of CH index vs k, the CH index is maximised at k = 2 not k = 6, which means when k = 2 a tighter cluster itself and a more dispersed cluster to cluster. – 2. From the cluster plot, when k = 2, two clusters are well separated. However when k = 6, many clusters overlap with each others. – 3. From the cluster dendrogram, When k=2, it is significantly more stable, and when k=6, one of the clusters even has only one data

print_clusters <- function(df, groups, cols_to_print) {
  Ngroups <- max(groups)
  for (i in 1:Ngroups) {
    print(paste("cluster", i))
    print(df[groups == i, cols_to_print])
  } 
}

Based on the previous analysis, we divided the sample set into two sets of 61 data based on the CAL_YR and CAL_QTR, which were sorted from 1 to 61 in order of time from smallest to largest. For each group, the Euclidean distance between ACCIDENT_NUM, M_SHIFT_BEGIN_TIME, M_NO_INJURIES, M_TOT_EXPER, M_MINE_EXPER and M_JOB_EXPER were used as the six dimensions for the kmeans clustering.

Cluster 1 mainly contains the number of accidents from 2005, with a lower number of accidents, later shift begin time and less work experience.

Cluster 2 mainly contains the number of accidents from 2000, with a larger number of accidents, earlier shift begin time and more work experience.

Clustering visualisation study

Visualize the clustering data

fviz_cluster(km_result, data = scaled_df,ellipse.type = "euclid",star.plot = TRUE, repel = TRUE,ggtheme = theme_minimal())

Afterwards we will visualise the sample set that has been clustered and study the two principal component dimensions obtained through the CPCA method of principal component analysis. The visualisation shows that groups with similar accident times as well as a similar number of accidents can be well clustered together, which can reflect the fact that accidents occur at different times and the factors they contain are similar.

As each group of data has six indicators, i.e. six dimensions, two principal component dimensions were obtained by means of principal component analysis (PCA) in order to be able to visualise them. The visualisation shows that groups with similar accident times can be well clustered together, which can reflect the fact that some of the factors included in the different times of accidents are similar and therefore our choice of k values is correct

If we divide the sample into 6 clusters

km_result_6 <- kmeans(scaled_df, 6)
fviz_cluster(km_result_6, data = scaled_df,ellipse.type = "euclid",star.plot = TRUE, repel = TRUE,ggtheme = theme_minimal())

As the figure above, k = 6 is too large for the sample set, resulting in a small number of samples in each cluster and an overfitting situation.

Show the cluster results

Now we show the cluster result by showing the clustering dendrogram. Hierarchical clustering using Euclidean distances was first used to find pairwise similarities between samples, and then the least variance method was used to generate a hierarchical ward least variance method.

result <- dist(data_cluster, method = "euclidean")
result_hc <- hclust(d = result, method = "ward.D2")
fviz_dend(result_hc, k = 2,
          color_labels_by_k = TRUE, 
          rect = TRUE          
)

fviz_dend(result_hc, k = 6, 
          color_labels_by_k = TRUE, 
          rect = TRUE          
)

As the chart above, there is very little room to divide the sample into six categories, and it would be better to divide it into two categories.

Conclusion

  1. We choose the Euclidean distance to measure the distance because the data are normalised,. The Euclidean distance in vector space can be a good evaluation of the distance between two sample points. Cosine similarity is the spatial vector used to determine the similarity of two sample points. In this task, there are too many sample points and they are relatively discrete, so the cosine similarity is not good.

  2. And we then let k = 2 and only divided the data into two classes, which seems so few and also far from the centre. Howerver, as the analysis above, let k = 2 is most suitable for this dataset because of three reasons, which are the CH index, cluster plot and the cluster dendrogram. The CH index is the ratio of separation to tightness. So a larger CH represents a tighter class itself and a more dispersed class to class.

  3. Finally, we find that Cluster 1 mainly contains the number of accidents from 2005, with a lower number of accidents, later shift begin time and less work experience. Cluster 2 mainly contains the number of accidents from 2000, with a larger number of accidents, earlier shift begin time and more work experience. This is consistent with our finding in project1 that the number of accidents has decreased over time. However, it seems that the quarter with more accidents also has more mean work experience, which we speculate may be because work experience does not play a big role in the number of accidents. In other words, it mainly depend on the time (the year, quarter and shift time).
